# Notion Board Standards

When creating Notion boards for ANY repository or project, follow this standard:

## Board structure
- A main hub page with clear navigation and inline board view
- An active-only execution database (no completed items cluttering the view)
- A dedicated Immediate Action Items page with meeting agenda and prep instructions
- A Phase Goals page with per-phase narrative, key tasks, and success criteria
- A Brainstorming Outline page with scoring rubric (user value, build effort, risk)
- Research notes as separate pages when vendor/technology decisions are involved
- Legacy/archive database kept separate for historical reference

## Phase naming
- Name phases with descriptive labels, not just numbers (e.g., "Phase 1- Discovery Launch" not "Phase 1")
- Each phase name should make the purpose immediately obvious

## Database columns
- Rich detail fields: Owner, Why This Matters, Definition of Done, Dependencies, Next Checkpoint (date), Notes
- Track type (Goal, Action Item, Immediate Action, Roadmap, Research, Risk, Decision)
- Priority (P0-P3), Status (Immediate, This Week, In Progress, Blocked, Planned)
- Source tags tracing where each item originated
- Owner fields should be LEFT BLANK for the user to assign when presenting to their team
- Prefer more phases with fewer tasks each (2-5 tasks per phase) over fewer phases with many tasks
- Phase names should be descriptive and numbered (e.g., "0: Lock the Plan", "3: Build the Discovery Engine")
- No meeting agendas, meeting prep, or meeting references. This is an action-oriented board.

## Task page content (most important)
- Every task must have a click-into detail page written for a NON-TECHNICAL audience
- Structure: What is this task? > Why are we doing this? > What does done look like? > Action items checklist > Discussion questions
- Use analogies to explain technical concepts in plain language
- Include step-by-step action item checklists inside each task
- Add discussion questions the team can use in meetings
- The owner should be able to read a task and confidently present/discuss it without a technical background

## Process
- Run a codebase audit (via explore agent) to find missing tasks before finalizing the board
- Use the Notion MCP tools (notion-create-database, notion-create-pages, notion-update-page) to build directly in Notion
- Batch page creation but keep batches small (3-4 pages) to avoid timeouts
